Projections for Covid-19 cases in Cote dâ€™Ivoire

Raphael Volz (rv@volzinnovation.com)

Last updated on 2020-10-14

Executive Summary: The first wave has ended in Cote dâ€™Ivoire on 2020-08-17 (Day 159). We expect a total of 20,634 cases in the first wave of the COVID-19 pandemic in Cote dâ€™Ivoire, this is an additional 451 cases compared to current case total. New cases have peeked on 2020-06-30 with 269 new cases. Our models assume that after end of the current wave around 53 new cases will appear on an average day, since SARS-CoV-2 is now endemic. Quick, effective, and differentiated mitigation measures need to be in place to prevent a new outbreak.

1 New Cases

According to the Johns Hopkins University global COVID-19 data set [1] a total of 20,183 COVID-19 cases were reported in Cote dâ€™Ivoire on 2020-10-13. This number of cases increased by 0 percent over the cumulative total cases known one day earlier. At this rate of cases double every days and the basic reproduction rate \(R_0\) in Cote dâ€™Ivoire can be estimated at 1.3, an estimate of the average number of other people infected by a single infected person. Figure 1.1 shows the time line of new cases reported in the country (black points) together with a five day moving average (purple line) that smoothes daily fluctuations in the reporting that are due to fewer capacities on weekends, holidays and other reporting mishaps.

Figure 1.1: New cases and five day moving average.

1.1 Model for new cases (DSM)

New cases peek after a certain time of growth that follows a sigmoidal function and then recedes to a lower level as the epidemic wave fades out and enters an endemic state. This behavior can be modelled with a double-sigmoid function \(f_{base}\), that is obtained by the product of two sigmoidal functions [2].

\[ f_{base}(t) = \frac{1}{ 1+e^{-\alpha_{i} * (t - t_{i})} } * \frac{1}{ 1+e^{-\alpha_{d} * (t - t_{d})} }\]

This function has a maximum \(f_{max} = max(f_{base}(t_{max}))\) at \(t_{max}\).

The model can obtain predictions related to an observed maximum of new cases \(I_{max_{d}}\) and an endemic number of daily cases \(I_{final_{d}}\) as an asymptote (that is ideally 0). Let \(f_{d}(t)\) be a piecewise function that switches between the growth and decay phase at \(t_{max}\), such that

\[\begin{aligned}f_{d}(t) = \left\{ \begin{array}{cc} \frac{I_{max_{d}}}{f_{max}} * f_{base}(t) & \hspace{5mm} t \leq t_{max} \\ \frac{I_{max_{d}} - I_{final_{d} }}{f_{max}} * f_{base}(t) + I_{final_{d}} & \hspace{5mm} t > t_{max} \\ \end{array} \right. \end{aligned}\]

where \(t_{i}\) is the midpoint and \(\alpha_{i}\) the slope of the increase of cases and \(t_{d}\) is the midpoint and \(\alpha_{d}\) is the slope of the decrease in cases. \(I_{max_{d}}\) the peak of new cases and \(I_{final_{d}}\) the asymptotic final value of new cases at the end of the infections wave. Figure 1.2 shows the current double-sigmoidal model ( orange line) that is fitted for the new case time series of Cote dâ€™Ivoire, where the vertical dashed line highlights the midpoint \(t_i\) of the growth phase, the vertical solid line indicates the peak of new infections \(t_max\) and the vertical dotted line the midpoint \(t_d\) of the decay phase. The dashed horizontal line marks the estimated asymptote of endemic new cases \(I_{final_{d}}\) as this infection wave ends. We pragmatically assume that the first wave ends, when 99 percent of the decrease has happened. The dashed green line marks this date.

Figure 1.2: Double sigmoidal model (DSM) for new cases.

1.2 Reliability of the DSM

Since the model requires six parameters, it also requires more data points. Hence, it is only feasible to fit this model in later phases of the pandemic (ideally after the peak of daily infections occured) and the model is highly sensitive to new data, particularly with respect to finding the final asymptote\(I_{final_{d}}\)as the following comparison of the model shows. Nevertheless the model renders interesting characteristica of the past developments.

2 Cumulative cases

The cumulative total of COVID-19 cases in Cote dâ€™Ivoire is the number of all COVID-19 cases known up to yesterday and includes all patients already recovered from the infection. This corresponds to the Infected (I) number in the standard epidemiological SIR model. Figure 2.1 shows the data points of the time series together with a Gompertz model for the cumulative cases (red line) as well as the cumulated double-sigmoidal model (orange line). The dashed horizontal lines show the expected maximum number of cases of the respective models. Note: The cumulated double-sigmoidal model does not have an asymptote, since \(I_{final_{d}}\) is not zero, the line can be considered as the number of infections when the infective wave ends and the endemic state starts.

Figure 2.1: Cumulative cases with DSM and Gompertz models

2.1 Gompertz model for cumulative cases

The Gompertz model [3] is a sigmoid model that is often fitted to growth data, and often prefered over the standard logistic model (als called Verhulst model) due its asymetry. The Gompertz can be considered as a special case of the four parameter Richards model and is computationally easier to fit as it has one parameter less. The model is based on the cumulative distribution function \(f_{c}(t)\), which is a three parameter logistic function:

\[ f_{c}(t) = I_{max_{c}} * e^{ - \beta_{c} * e^{ - \alpha_{c} * t }} \]

Where the parameter \(I_{max_{c}}\) is the estimated maximum number of cumulative cases (asymptote), \(\beta_{c}\) inflects the curve along time, and \(\alpha_{c}\) is the maximum absolute growth rate of cumulated cases.

2.2 Reliability of the Gompertz model

The Gompertz model change over time as new data is available. Obviously, we are interested whether the models are reliable and in particular show some convergence. When we compare the current model with the model calculated using the information that was available last week, we can again observe how the model parameters have changed.

Parameter Current Estimate Last Week Estimate Delta (absolute)

3 Projections

3.1 Methodology

Putting in future dates into the current models allows to project future cases. Note: The actual development can differ from model predictions, for example if social distancing norms change or methods in data collection are altered. If such changes happen, a model fitted to the past is no longer valid.

Figure 3.1: Nowcast of past models for yesterday

3.2 Nowcast

Yesterday 20183 COVID-19 cases were known in Cote dâ€™Ivoire [1]. Figure 3.1 illustrates how past Gompertz models (red line) have predicted the last known number of cumulative COVID-19 cases (dashed black line). The lightblue shaded area indicates that the Gompertz model of 2020-08-21 (day 164) and all later models could predict the case number for 2020-10-13 with at most 2 percent difference to the actual case numbers. Hence, the Gompertz models could reliably predict the actual case numbers for the coming 53 days.

4 Discussion and outlook

Epidemiological models are useful for policy makers, e.g.Â to assess needed ICU beds, required (additional) restrictions of daily life, etc. However models require (often disputed) assumptions for model parameters. The data-driven approach demonstrated here avoids parameter assumptions and uses past data to fit models that not only describe the past developments but provide reliable forecasts for the nearer future of an epidemic. Next to policy makers, the general public can use the projections to assess their expectations when business or schools might reopen (or reclose).

As a next step data about the population and population structure could be used to compare between countries, for example to assess the effectiveness of different public policies for controlling the disease.
